For a field producing 100,000 boe/d, even a 2% improvement in production rate at \$60/bbl translates to over \$40 million per year in additional revenue.

== The Production Value Chain
<the-production-value-chain-1>
=== Reservoir
<reservoir-1>
The reservoir is the source of all production. Key properties include:

- #strong[Reservoir pressure] --- the driving force for production, declining over time
- #strong[Reservoir temperature] --- affects fluid properties and phase behavior
- #strong[Fluid composition] --- determines the products (oil, gas, condensate, water) and processing requirements
- #strong[Permeability and porosity] --- control the rate at which fluids flow to the wellbore

The reservoir imposes the ultimate constraint on production: once the pressure is depleted and the mobile hydrocarbons are swept, production ends regardless of the facility capacity.

=== Wells
<wells-1>
Wells connect the reservoir to the surface. Their design and performance directly affect production rate:

- #strong[Inflow Performance Relationship (IPR)] --- the rate at which fluid flows from the reservoir into the wellbore as a function of bottomhole pressure
- #strong[Vertical Flow Performance (VFP)] --- the pressure loss in the tubing from bottomhole to wellhead
- #strong[Artificial lift] --- gas lift, ESPs, or rod pumps to augment natural flow when reservoir pressure declines
- #strong[Choke control] --- wellhead chokes regulate production rate and protect downstream equipment

=== Subsea Production Systems
<subsea-production-systems-1>
In offshore fields, the subsea system is often the link between wells and surface facilities:

- #strong[Subsea trees (Christmas trees)] --- wellhead valve assemblies on the seabed
- #strong[Manifolds] --- collect production from multiple wells
- #strong[Flowlines] --- transport multiphase flow from manifold to riser base
- #strong[Risers] --- carry production from seabed to the surface facility
- #strong[Subsea boosting and processing] --- pumps, compressors, and separators on the seabed

=== Topside Processing Facilities
<topside-processing-facilities-1>
The topside facility (platform, FPSO, or onshore plant) separates, treats, and conditions the produced fluids:

- #strong[Separation] --- HP, MP, LP separators to separate gas, oil, and water
- #strong[Oil processing] --- dewatering, desalting, stabilization
- #strong[Gas processing] --- dehydration, dew point control, NGL recovery, CO$""_2$ removal
- #strong[Gas compression] --- recompression, export compression, gas lift compression, injection compression
- #strong[Produced water treatment] --- oil removal, chemical treatment, discharge or reinjection
- #strong[Utilities] --- power generation, heat medium, flare system

=== Export and Market
<export-and-market>
The final stage delivers products to market:

- #strong[Oil export] --- pipeline or shuttle tanker offloading
- #strong[Gas export] --- pipeline to onshore terminal or LNG plant
- #strong[Fiscal metering] --- custody transfer measurement per ISO and AGA standards
- #strong[Quality specification compliance] --- heating value, Wobbe index, water content, H$""_2$S content

== The Role of Process Simulation
<the-role-of-process-simulation-1>
Process simulation is the computational backbone of production optimization. A calibrated process model predicts how the production system responds to changes in operating conditions --- flow rates, pressures, temperatures, compositions --- without the cost and risk of physical experimentation.

=== Steady-State vs.~Dynamic Simulation
<steady-state-vs.-dynamic-simulation-1>
#strong[Steady-state simulation] calculates the equilibrium operating point of a process given fixed inputs. It is used for: - Capacity checks and equipment rating - Design verification - "What-if" scenarios (what happens if we increase well rates?) - Optimization (find the best operating point)

#strong[Dynamic simulation] tracks how the process evolves over time, including startup, shutdown, and transient events. It is used for: - Control system design and tuning - Slug flow impact assessment - Emergency depressurization studies - Compressor anti-surge system verification

NeqSim supports both steady-state and dynamic simulation through its `ProcessSystem` framework.

=== Why NeqSim?
<why-neqsim-1>
NeqSim is an open-source Java library for thermodynamic and process simulation with several characteristics that make it well-suited for production optimization:

- #strong[Rigorous thermodynamics] --- multiple equations of state (SRK, PR, CPA, Electrolyte CPA) ensure accurate fluid property predictions
- #strong[Complete process equipment library] --- separators, compressors, heat exchangers, valves, pipes, columns, and more
- #strong[Multiphase pipe flow] --- Beggs and Brill correlation for pipelines and risers
- #strong[Dynamic simulation] --- transient capability with PID controllers and measurement devices
- #strong[Python interface] --- access the full Java engine from Python/Jupyter notebooks
- #strong[Equipment rating] --- capacity checks, compressor curves, valve Cv calculations
- #strong[Open source] --- inspect, modify, and extend the source code

