== EOS Parameter Tuning
<eos-parameter-tuning>
=== Why Tuning Is Necessary
<why-tuning-is-necessary>
Default EOS parameters (from generalized correlations) typically give acceptable results for defined components but may be inaccurate for the pseudo-components representing the plus fraction. The critical properties assigned to pseudo-components are estimates, and small errors in $T_c$, $P_c$, or $omega$ propagate into significant errors in saturation pressure and liquid density. Tuning adjusts selected parameters to match experimental PVT data.

=== Binary Interaction Parameters ($k_(i j)$)
<binary-interaction-parameters-k-ij>
The binary interaction parameter modifies the attractive term in the EOS mixing rule:

$ a_(upright("mix")) = sum_i sum_j x_i x_j sqrt(a_i a_j) \( 1 - k_(i j) \) $

A positive $k_(i j)$ reduces the effective attraction between components $i$ and $j$, generally increasing the saturation pressure and reducing miscibility. The most sensitive BIPs for production optimization are:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 3,
    align: (auto,auto,auto,),
    table.header([Component Pair], [Typical $k_(i j)$ Range], [Primary Effect],),
    table.hline(),
    [CH$""_4$ -- C$""_(7 +)$], [0.02--0.06], [Bubble/dew point pressure],
    [CO$""_2$ -- C$""_(7 +)$], [0.10--0.15], [CO$""_2$ solubility, MMP],
    [N$""_2$ -- C$""_(7 +)$], [0.05--0.10], [N$""_2$ rejection efficiency],
    [CH$""_4$ -- CO$""_2$], [0.10--0.13], [Gas phase density],
  )]
  , kind: table
  )

=== Volume Translation
<volume-translation>
Cubic equations of state (SRK, PR) systematically underpredict liquid density by 5--15%. The Peneloux volume translation corrects this without affecting the phase equilibrium calculation:

$ v_(upright("corrected")) = v_(upright("EOS")) - sum_i x_i c_i $

where $c_i$ is the volume shift parameter for component $i$. For pseudo-components, $c_i$ is tuned to match the measured liquid density at reservoir conditions.

=== Matching Priority and Tolerances
<matching-priority-and-tolerances>
The order of matching priority for production optimization is:

+ #strong[Saturation pressure] --- bubble point or dew point (highest priority)
+ #strong[Liquid density / oil FVF] --- affects volumetric calculations
+ #strong[Gas-oil ratio] --- separator test GOR
+ #strong[Liquid dropout] --- for gas condensates (CVD)
+ #strong[Viscosity] --- affects pressure drop calculations

Acceptable tolerances for tuned models:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 2,
    align: (auto,auto,),
    table.header([Property], [Target Accuracy],),
    table.hline(),
    [Saturation pressure], [±1--2%],
    [Liquid density], [±1--2%],
    [GOR], [±3--5%],
    [Liquid dropout (CVD)], [±10% of peak],
    [Viscosity], [±10--15%],
  )]
  , kind: table
  )

=== Regression Workflow
<regression-workflow>
A systematic tuning workflow:

+ #strong[Start with default parameters] and compare against experimental data
+ #strong[Adjust plus fraction molecular weight] (±10%) to match saturation pressure
+ #strong[Tune $k_(i j)$] between methane and heavy pseudo-components to refine saturation pressure and liquid dropout
+ #strong[Adjust volume shift] to match liquid density
+ #strong[Check separator test] GOR and API gravity
+ #strong[Verify phase envelope] shape and critical point location
+ #strong[Iterate] until all experimental data are matched within acceptable tolerances

=== Tuning in NeqSim
<tuning-in-neqsim>
