=== Selection Criteria
<selection-criteria>
The choice of architecture is driven by:

- #strong[Reservoir geometry]: Elongated reservoirs suit daisy-chain; compact reservoirs suit cluster manifolds
- #strong[Number of wells and phasing]: Template architectures are efficient for large, fully defined developments; modular manifolds suit phased drilling campaigns
- #strong[Distance to host]: Satellite wells are uneconomic beyond \~15 km due to per-well flowline costs; cluster manifolds become advantageous for longer tiebacks
- #strong[Seabed terrain]: Rough seabed or steep slopes may dictate flowline routing and manifold placement
- #strong[Flow assurance]: High wax or hydrate risk may favor architectures with pigging capability (cluster manifold with pigging loop) over daisy chain (difficult to pig)
- #strong[Expansion potential]: If additional wells may be drilled later, the architecture should accommodate future tie-ins

== Subsea vs.~Dry Tree Completions
<subsea-vs.-dry-tree-completions>
The choice between subsea (wet tree) and dry tree completions is one of the most consequential decisions in offshore field development. It affects capital cost, operating cost, production efficiency, intervention frequency, and ultimately recovery factor.

=== Dry Tree Platforms
<dry-tree-platforms>
Dry tree completions place the wellheads on the platform deck, providing direct access for wireline, coiled tubing, and workover operations. Platform types that support dry trees include:

- #strong[Fixed platforms] --- jacket or gravity-based structures in shallow water (\< 300 m)
- #strong[Compliant towers] --- for moderate water depths (300--600 m)
- #strong[Tension Leg Platforms (TLPs)] --- taut-moored for deepwater (500--1,500 m)
- #strong[Spars] --- deep-draft cylindrical hulls (500--2,500 m)

The primary advantage of dry trees is well access. Wireline and coiled tubing operations that cost \$200,000 and take 2 days from a platform may cost \$5,000,000 and take 3 weeks from a subsea intervention vessel.

=== Decision Criteria
<decision-criteria>
