== Subsea Architecture and Components
<subsea-architecture-and-components-1>
=== Subsea Christmas Trees
<subsea-christmas-trees-1>
The subsea tree (also known as a Christmas tree or wet tree) is the primary well control device installed on the seabed. It sits atop the wellhead and provides:

- #strong[Flow control] --- master valves and wing valves regulate production
- #strong[Well shut-in] --- fail-safe closed valves for emergency and planned shutdowns
- #strong[Chemical injection points] --- for hydrate inhibitor, corrosion inhibitor, and scale inhibitor injection
- #strong[Monitoring] --- pressure and temperature sensors for well surveillance
- #strong[Intervention access] --- through-bore access for wireline or coiled tubing operations

Two main configurations exist:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 3,
    align: (auto,auto,auto,),
    table.header([Feature], [Vertical Tree], [Horizontal Tree],),
    table.hline(),
    [Master valve orientation], [Vertical bore], [Horizontal bore],
    [Tubing hanger location], [In the tree], [In the wellhead],
    [Tree retrieval], [Requires tubing pull], [Independent of tubing],
    [Bore access], [Through tree], [Through tree cap],
    [Typical application], [Moderate depth], [Deepwater, HP/HT],
    [Well intervention], [More complex], [Simpler],
    [Cost (typical)], [\$15--25M], [\$20--35M],
  )]
  , kind: table
  )

Horizontal trees have become the standard for deepwater developments because they allow the tree to be installed and retrieved independently of the tubing string, simplifying intervention operations.

=== Subsea Manifolds
<subsea-manifolds-1>
A subsea manifold collects production from multiple wells and routes it into a common flowline. Key design parameters include:

- #strong[Number of slots] --- typically 4 to 8 well connections
- #strong[Pressure rating] --- matched to the maximum shut-in tubing head pressure (SITHP)
- #strong[Bore size] --- determines flow capacity; typically 4” to 6” production bores
- #strong[Valve configuration] --- individual well isolation and crossover capability
- #strong[Weight and footprint] --- affects installation vessel requirements

Manifolds enable the commingling of production, reducing the number of flowlines required from the subsea field to the host. For example, a field with 12 wells and two 6-slot manifolds requires only 2 production flowlines rather than 12 individual well flowlines.

=== Templates and Foundations
<templates-and-foundations-1>
Subsea templates are structural frames installed on the seabed to guide the positioning of wells, trees, and manifolds. Templates provide:

- #strong[Well slot positioning] --- precise spacing for drilling and completion
- #strong[Structural support] --- for trees, manifolds, and jumpers
- #strong[Mudmat or suction anchor foundations] --- resist lateral and vertical loads
- #strong[Pipeline end terminations (PLETs)] --- connection points for flowlines

Template design must account for seabed soil conditions, current loads, installation tolerances, and the weight of installed equipment. A typical 4-slot template weighs 300--600 tonnes.

=== Jumpers and Connections
<jumpers-and-connections-1>
Jumpers are short pipe sections that connect subsea trees to manifolds, or manifolds to flowlines. They accommodate installation tolerances and thermal expansion:

- #strong[Rigid jumpers] --- steel pipe, typically 6”--10” diameter, with mechanical connectors
- #strong[Flexible jumpers] --- multi-layered flexible pipe, used where large deflections are expected
- #strong[Typical length] --- 20 to 100 meters

Connection systems include:

