=== Blending Optimization
<blending-optimization>
On multi-well platforms or in commingled pipelines, the export crude is a blend of production from several reservoirs with different properties. Blending optimization seeks to maximize the value of the commingled stream while meeting all quality constraints.

For simple blending of $n$ streams, the blend properties can be estimated using mixing rules:

#strong[Volume-additive properties] (API gravity, density):

$ rho_(upright("blend")) = sum_i f_i rho_i $

where $f_i$ is the volume fraction of stream $i$.

#strong[Non-linear properties] (RVP):

$ upright("RVP")_(upright("blend"))^1.25 = sum_i x_i upright("RVP")_i^1.25 $

This is the Chevron blending index correlation, which provides a reasonable approximation for RVP blending. For rigorous calculations, the entire blend must be flashed in NeqSim.

== Oil Heating, Cooling, and Wax Management
<oil-heating-cooling-and-wax-management>
=== Crude Oil Heating
<crude-oil-heating>
Oil heating is required at several points in the processing train:

- #strong[Before the stabilizer column]: Oil is preheated to 80--120°C to achieve the required flash temperature and reduce reboiler duty
- #strong[Before the desalter]: Heating to 120--150°C reduces oil viscosity for better water separation
- #strong[For heavy oil transport]: Heating reduces viscosity to allow pipeline pumping

Common heat sources include:

- #strong[Cross-exchange with hot process streams] (compressed gas, hot stabilizer bottoms)
- #strong[Hot produced water] (available at 60--90°C, often the primary heat source)
- #strong[Waste heat from gas turbines] (exhaust at 450--550°C, available via heat recovery steam generators)
- #strong[Fired heaters] (used when other sources are insufficient, especially for stabilizer reboilers)

=== Oil Cooling Before Export
<oil-cooling-before-export>
Stabilized crude oil leaving the reboiler or last separator may be too hot for direct export. Export temperature limits (typically \< 60°C) are imposed to:

- Prevent thermal damage to pipeline coatings
- Limit vapor generation in cargo tanks during tanker loading
- Meet contractual temperature specifications

Crude oil coolers (typically shell-and-tube or plate-frame heat exchangers) cool the export oil using seawater or air cooling. The cooler design must account for the potential for wax deposition on cold heat transfer surfaces --- a minimum wall temperature is maintained above the wax appearance temperature (WAT) to prevent fouling.

=== Pour Point and Wax Management
<pour-point-and-wax-management>
The pour point of crude oil is the lowest temperature at which the oil flows under standard test conditions (ASTM D97). It is governed by the crystallization of paraffin wax molecules (typically C$""_18$--C$""_40$ normal alkanes). When the oil temperature approaches the pour point:

- #strong[Wax crystals form] and create a gel structure that immobilizes the liquid
- #strong[Viscosity increases dramatically] (by 2--4 orders of magnitude over a narrow temperature range)
- #strong[Pipeline restart after shutdown] becomes extremely difficult due to the high gel strength

Wax management strategies in oil processing include:

- #strong[Heating]: Maintain oil temperature above WAT throughout the processing and transport chain
- #strong[Pour point depressants (PPDs)]: Chemical additives that modify wax crystal morphology, reducing pour point by 10--30°C
- #strong[Pigging]: Regular passage of pipeline pigs to remove deposited wax
- #strong[Blending]: Mixing waxy crude with lighter diluent to reduce pour point and viscosity
- #strong[Insulation]: Pipeline insulation to maintain temperature above WAT during transport

== Heavy Oil Processing
<heavy-oil-processing>
=== Challenges with Heavy Oil
<challenges-with-heavy-oil>
Heavy oils (API gravity \< 22°) and extra-heavy oils (API \< 10°) present unique processing challenges:

