== Produced Water Reinjection (PWRI)
<produced-water-reinjection-pwri>
Produced water reinjection is increasingly preferred over overboard discharge for both environmental and reservoir management reasons. In PWRI, treated produced water is injected into the producing reservoir (for pressure maintenance) or into a dedicated disposal formation.

=== Injectivity and Formation Damage
<injectivity-and-formation-damage>
The injectivity index defines the relationship between injection rate and bottomhole pressure:

$ I I = frac(Q_(upright("inj")), P_(upright("BH")) - P_(upright("res"))) $

where $Q_(upright("inj"))$ is the injection rate, $P_(upright("BH"))$ is the bottomhole injection pressure, and $P_(upright("res"))$ is the reservoir pressure.

Formation damage from produced water injection manifests as declining injectivity over time. The principal mechanisms are:

+ #strong[Suspended solids plugging]: Particles in the water block pore throats near the wellbore. The critical particle size is related to the median pore throat diameter:

$ d_(upright("crit")) approx 1 / 3 d_(upright("pore,50")) $

#block[
#set enum(numbering: "1.", start: 2)
+ #strong[Oil droplet retention]: Dispersed oil can block pore throats and alter wettability, reducing permeability near the wellbore.
+ #strong[Scale precipitation]: When injected water mixes with formation water or when pressure and temperature conditions change, mineral scales (e.g., barium sulfate, calcium carbonate) may precipitate.
+ #strong[Biological growth]: Bacteria (particularly sulfate-reducing bacteria, SRB) can form biofilms that plug the formation.
]

=== Water Quality Specifications for PWRI
<water-quality-specifications-for-pwri>
Water quality requirements for reinjection are specific to each field and depend on formation permeability, fracture pressure, and injection strategy:

