== Pressure Relief Systems
<pressure-relief-systems>
=== Purpose and Regulatory Requirements
<purpose-and-regulatory-requirements>
Pressure relief systems are the last line of defense against overpressure. They are required by:

- #strong[ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code] (Section VIII) --- requires overpressure protection for all pressure vessels
- #strong[API 520] --- sizing, selection, and installation of pressure-relieving devices
- #strong[API 521] --- guide for pressure-relieving and depressuring systems
- #strong[NORSOK P-001] --- process design (Norwegian Continental Shelf)
- #strong[PED 2014/68/EU] --- Pressure Equipment Directive (Europe)

=== Types of Pressure Relief Devices
<types-of-pressure-relief-devices>
#strong[Pressure Safety Valves (PSVs)] --- spring-loaded valves that open at a set pressure: - #strong[Conventional PSV] --- back-pressure affects the set point; used with atmospheric or low-backpressure discharge - #strong[Balanced bellows PSV] --- back-pressure compensated; used with variable backpressure (flare header) - #strong[Pilot-operated PSV] --- pilot valve controls the main valve; used for very tight shutoff or high backpressure

#strong[Rupture Discs] --- thin metal discs that burst at a calibrated pressure: - Provide full bore opening instantly - Cannot reclose --- require replacement after activation - Used as a primary device for corrosive fluids or as a backup upstream of a PSV

=== Relief Scenarios
<relief-scenarios>
API 521 identifies the following overpressure scenarios that must be evaluated:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 3,
    align: (auto,auto,auto,),
    table.header([Scenario], [Description], [Typical Governing Case],),
    table.hline(),
    [Fire case], [External fire raises pressure], [Large liquid-containing vessels],
    [Blocked outlet], [Downstream valve closed], [Pumps, compressors],
    [Thermal expansion], [Trapped liquid heated], [Isolated pipe sections],
    [Loss of cooling], [Cooling water or air cooler failure], [Condensers, coolers],
    [Power failure], [All electrically driven equipment stops], [Entire process],
    [Instrument failure], [Control valve fails open/closed], [Depends on failure mode],
    [Chemical reaction], [Runaway exothermic reaction], [Reactors],
    [Tube rupture], [High-pressure fluid enters low-pressure side], [Heat exchangers],
  )]
  , kind: table
  )

=== PSV Sizing --- Gas Service
<psv-sizing-gas-service>
For gas service, the API 520 orifice area is:

$ A = frac(W, C K_d P_1 K_b K_c) sqrt(frac(T Z, M)) $

where: - $A$ = required effective discharge area (mm²) - $W$ = required relief rate (kg/hr) - $C$ = coefficient determined from the ratio of specific heats: $C = 0.03948 sqrt(k (frac(2, k + 1))^(\( k + 1 \) \/ \( k - 1 \)))$ - $K_d$ = effective coefficient of discharge (0.975 for vapor, 0.65 for liquid) - $P_1$ = relieving pressure (set pressure × 1.1 + atmospheric) - $K_b$ = back-pressure correction factor - $K_c$ = combination correction factor (1.0 for PSV alone, 0.9 for rupture disc + PSV) - $T$ = relieving temperature (K) - $Z$ = compressibility factor - $M$ = molecular weight

=== PSV Sizing --- Liquid Service
<psv-sizing-liquid-service>
For liquid service (incompressible flow):

$ A = frac(Q, 38.0 K_d K_w K_c K_p) sqrt(frac(G, P_1 - P_2)) $

where $Q$ is the volumetric flow (L/min), $G$ is the specific gravity, $K_w$ is the back-pressure correction, and $K_p$ is the overpressure correction.

=== Fire Case Sizing
<fire-case-sizing>
The fire case is often the governing scenario for PSV sizing on liquid-containing vessels. The relief rate is determined by the heat input from the fire:

$ Q_(upright("fire")) = C_1 F A_w^0.82 $

where: - $C_1$ = 43,200 (with adequate drainage) or 70,900 (without) in SI units - $F$ = environment factor (1.0 for bare vessel, 0.3 for fireproofed) - $A_w$ = wetted surface area up to the height of 7.6 m (m²)

The relief rate is then:

$ W = frac(Q_(upright("fire")), Delta H_(upright("vap"))) $

where $Delta H_(upright("vap"))$ is the latent heat of vaporization at the relieving conditions.

