== Flare System Design
<flare-system-design>
=== Purpose
<purpose>
The flare system collects and safely disposes of hydrocarbon vapors released from pressure relief devices, process vents, and emergency depressurization. The major components are:

- #strong[Flare header] --- collects relief and blowdown streams; sized for the maximum simultaneous relief case
- #strong[Knockout drum] --- separates liquids from the gas stream before the flare tip
- #strong[Flare stack or boom] --- elevates the flare tip to ensure safe dispersion of radiant heat and combustion products
- #strong[Pilot and ignition system] --- ensures reliable ignition of the flare gas
- #strong[Seal drum] --- prevents flashback from the flare tip into the header

=== Flare Header Sizing
<flare-header-sizing>
The flare header is sized using the API 521 momentum criterion:

$ rho v^2 lt.eq C_(upright("momentum")) $

where $rho$ is the gas density and $v$ is the velocity. API 521 recommends $rho v^2 lt.eq 100 \, 000$ Pa (for carbon steel piping) as the Mach number-based criterion for noise and vibration.

The flare tip diameter is sized to maintain a Mach number below 0.5 for normal operation and 0.8 for emergency:

$ d_(upright("tip")) = sqrt(frac(4 dot(m), pi rho v_max)) $

=== Radiation Analysis
<radiation-analysis>
The thermal radiation from the flare must be below safe limits at grade level and on the platform:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 2,
    align: (auto,auto,),
    table.header([Location], [Maximum Radiation (kW/m²)],),
    table.hline(),
    [Continuously occupied area], [1.58],
    [Personnel with brief exposure], [4.73],
    [Equipment (8 hours)], [6.31],
    [Emergency operations (short time)], [9.46],
    [Flare structure design], [15.8],
  )]
  , kind: table
  )

The radiation from an elevated flare is calculated using the API 521 point source model:

$ I = frac(F dot.op Q_(upright("fire")) dot.op tau, 4 pi D^2) $

where $F$ is the fraction of heat radiated (0.1--0.3), $Q_(upright("fire"))$ is the heat release rate, $tau$ is the atmospheric transmissivity, and $D$ is the distance from the flame center to the receiver.

