== Summary
<summary>
This chapter covered the theory and practice of valves, flow control, and pressure relief in oil and gas production:

- #strong[Flow coefficient] --- $C_v$ (US) and $K_v$ (SI) quantify a valve's flow capacity; the ISA/IEC 60534 standard provides rigorous sizing equations for both gas and liquid service
- #strong[Valve characteristics] --- linear, equal percentage, and quick opening curves describe how flow varies with valve travel; the installed characteristic depends on valve authority
- #strong[Valve types] --- globe valves dominate control applications; ball valves serve severe service and on/off duty; butterfly and gate valves handle large flows and isolation
- #strong[Choke valves] --- operate in subcritical or critical flow regimes; critical flow acts as a natural flow limiter where downstream pressure changes do not affect flow rate
- #strong[Joule-Thomson effect] --- isenthalpic expansion through valves causes cooling in real gases; this is both a processing tool (low-temperature separation) and a hazard (hydrate formation)
- #strong[Pressure relief] --- API 520/521 governs PSV sizing for gas, liquid, and fire cases; the fire case often governs for liquid-containing vessels
- #strong[Flare systems] --- collect and safely dispose of relief discharges; sized based on the maximum simultaneous relief case
- #strong[NeqSim modeling] --- the `ThrottlingValve` class supports $C_v$-based flow, isenthalpic flash, partial valve opening, and integration into complete production system models

