=== Prover Systems
<prover-systems>
A prover is a calibrated reference device used to verify and adjust the K-factor of a fiscal meter in situ. The most common types are:

#strong[Conventional (bidirectional) pipe prover]: A precisely measured volume of pipe (between two detector switches) through which a displacer sphere or piston travels. The meter's pulse count during the known volume displacement gives the K-factor:

$ K = N_(upright("pulses")) / V_(upright("prover")) dot.op C_(upright("tsp")) dot.op C_(upright("psp")) dot.op C_(upright("tlm")) dot.op C_(upright("plm")) $

where $V_(upright("prover"))$ is the prover base volume, $C_(upright("tsp"))$ and $C_(upright("psp"))$ are the temperature and pressure corrections for the prover steel, and $C_(upright("tlm"))$ and $C_(upright("plm"))$ are the temperature and pressure corrections for the liquid in the meter.

#strong[Small volume prover (compact prover)]: Uses a precision piston in a smaller volume, requiring higher reproducibility per pass. Typical uncertainty: ±0.02% on prover volume.

#strong[Master meter]: A calibrated reference meter (usually Coriolis or turbine) used to verify the fiscal meter. Requires periodic recalibration against a primary prover.

