== Debottlenecking Economics
<debottlenecking-economics-1>
=== Cost-Benefit Analysis Framework
<cost-benefit-analysis-framework>
Debottlenecking investments must be evaluated against the incremental revenue they generate. The fundamental economic metric is the #strong[debottlenecking value ratio] --- the ratio of incremental production value to modification cost:

$ upright("Value Ratio") = frac(Delta Q times P_(upright("oil")) times T_(upright("remaining")), C_(upright("modification"))) $

where $Delta Q$ is the production gain \[bbl/d\], $P_(upright("oil"))$ is the oil price \[\$/bbl\], $T_(upright("remaining"))$ is the remaining field life \[years\], and $C_(upright("modification"))$ is the total installed cost of the modification \[\$\]. A value ratio greater than 3--5 is typically required to justify the investment, given the uncertainties in production forecasts and commodity prices.

=== Simple Payback Period
<simple-payback-period>
The #strong[simple payback period] is the most commonly used screening metric for debottlenecking projects:

$ T_(upright("payback")) = frac(C_(upright("modification")), Delta Q times P_(upright("oil")) times 365) $

For example, if a compressor driver uprate costs 45 MNOK and delivers 5,000 bbl/d additional oil at \$70/bbl:

$ T_(upright("payback")) = frac(45 times 10^6, 5 \, 000 times 70 times 365) = 0.35 upright(" years") approx 4.2 upright(" months") $

Projects with payback periods less than 12 months are typically fast-tracked. Projects with payback between 1 and 3 years require more detailed economic evaluation. Projects exceeding 3 years are rarely justified for debottlenecking alone.

=== NPV and IRR for Debottlenecking Modifications
<npv-and-irr-for-debottlenecking-modifications>
For larger investments or when timing of cash flows matters, the #strong[Net Present Value (NPV)] provides a more rigorous assessment:

$ upright("NPV") = - C_0 + sum_(t = 1)^N frac(Delta Q_t times P_t - Delta upright("OPEX")_t, \( 1 + r \)^t) $

where $C_0$ is the initial investment, $Delta Q_t$ is the production gain in year $t$ (which may decline as the reservoir depletes), $P_t$ is the oil price in year $t$, $Delta upright("OPEX")_t$ is the incremental operating cost (maintenance, energy, chemicals), and $r$ is the discount rate.

The #strong[Internal Rate of Return (IRR)] is the discount rate at which NPV = 0. Debottlenecking projects typically exhibit very high IRRs (50--200%) because the initial investment is small relative to the incremental production value.

=== Typical Debottlenecking Costs
<typical-debottlenecking-costs>
The following table provides order-of-magnitude costs for common debottlenecking modifications on offshore platforms (Norwegian Continental Shelf, 2024 cost level):

