== Mathematical Formulation
<mathematical-formulation>
=== The General Optimization Problem
<the-general-optimization-problem>
A production optimization problem has the standard form:

$ max_x quad f \( x \) $

$ upright("subject to:") quad g_i \( x \) lt.eq 0 \, quad i = 1 \, dots.h \, m $

$ h_j \( x \) = 0 \, quad j = 1 \, dots.h \, p $

$ x^L lt.eq x lt.eq x^U $

where:

- $x in bb(R)^n$ is the vector of #strong[decision variables] (set points, valve positions, flow rates)
- $f \( x \)$ is the #strong[objective function] (production rate, revenue, efficiency)
- $g_i \( x \) lt.eq 0$ are #strong[inequality constraints] (equipment capacity limits, quality specifications)
- $h_j \( x \) = 0$ are #strong[equality constraints] (material balances, energy balances --- typically handled implicitly by the process simulator)
- $x^L$ and $x^U$ are the #strong[lower and upper bounds] on the decision variables

=== Objective Functions
<objective-functions>
The choice of objective function defines what "optimal" means. Common objectives in production optimization include:

#strong[Maximum oil production rate:]

$ f \( x \) = Q_(upright("oil")) \( x \) quad \[ upright("Sm")^3 \/ upright("day") \] $

#strong[Maximum revenue:]

$ f \( x \) = P_(upright("oil")) dot.op Q_(upright("oil")) \( x \) + P_(upright("gas")) dot.op Q_(upright("gas")) \( x \) - C_(upright("opex")) \( x \) $

where $P_(upright("oil"))$ and $P_(upright("gas"))$ are the prices of oil and gas, and $C_(upright("opex"))$ includes energy costs, chemical injection costs, etc.

#strong[Maximum recovery factor:]

$ f \( x \) = frac(integral_0^T Q_(upright("oil")) \( x \, t \) thin d t, upright("STOIIP")) $

#strong[Minimum specific energy consumption:]

$ f \( x \) = frac(W_(upright("total")) \( x \), Q_(upright("oil")) \( x \) + Q_(upright("gas,export")) \( x \)) quad \[ upright("kWh/Sm")^3 \] $

