== Multi-Objective Optimization
<multi-objective-optimization>
=== Concept
<concept>
Many production optimization problems have multiple competing objectives. For example:

- #strong[Maximize oil production] vs #strong[minimize energy consumption]
- #strong[Maximize gas export volume] vs #strong[maximize gas heating value]
- #strong[Maximize recovery factor] vs #strong[minimize water handling cost]

In multi-objective optimization, there is generally no single solution that optimizes all objectives simultaneously. Instead, there is a #strong[Pareto front] --- a set of solutions where no objective can be improved without worsening another.

=== Pareto Optimality
<pareto-optimality>
A solution $x^(*)$ is #strong[Pareto optimal] if there is no other feasible solution $x$ such that:

$ f_k \( x \) gt.eq f_k \( x^(*) \) quad forall k \, quad upright("and") quad f_j \( x \) > f_j \( x^(*) \) quad upright("for some ") j $

The set of all Pareto-optimal solutions is the #strong[Pareto front] in objective space.

=== Solution Approaches
<solution-approaches>
#strong[Weighted Sum Method:]

Convert multiple objectives into a single objective using weights:

$ max_x quad sum_(k = 1)^K w_k dot.op f_k \( x \) \, quad upright("where") quad sum_(k = 1)^K w_k = 1 \, quad w_k gt.eq 0 $

By varying the weights, different points on the Pareto front are obtained. This is simple but cannot find solutions on non-convex portions of the Pareto front.

#strong[$epsilon.alt$-Constraint Method:]

Optimize one objective while constraining the others:

$ max_x quad f_1 \( x \) quad upright("s.t.") quad f_k \( x \) gt.eq epsilon.alt_k \, quad k = 2 \, dots.h \, K $

By varying $epsilon.alt_k$, the entire Pareto front (including non-convex regions) can be traced.

#strong[Evolutionary Multi-Objective Optimization (NSGA-II):]

The Non-dominated Sorting Genetic Algorithm II (NSGA-II) maintains a population of solutions and uses non-dominated sorting and crowding distance to evolve toward the Pareto front in a single run.

=== Example: Oil Rate vs Power Consumption
<example-oil-rate-vs-power-consumption>
