== Real-Time Optimization (RTO)
<real-time-optimization-rto>
=== Architecture
<architecture>
Real-time optimization (RTO) is the automated, continuous optimization of a production facility using live plant data. The standard RTO architecture consists of four layers:

+ #strong[Data validation]: Clean and reconcile plant measurements (gross error detection, data reconciliation)
+ #strong[Parameter estimation]: Update the process model to match current plant conditions (model tuning)
+ #strong[Optimization]: Solve the optimization problem using the updated model
+ #strong[Implementation]: Send optimized set points to the control system

$ upright("Plant") arrow.r^(upright("measurements")) upright("Data Validation") arrow.r^(upright("clean data")) upright("Model Update") arrow.r^(upright("tuned model")) upright("Optimizer") arrow.r^(upright("set points")) upright("DCS") $

=== Steady-State vs Dynamic RTO
<steady-state-vs-dynamic-rto>
#strong[Steady-state RTO] assumes the plant is at (or near) steady state. It runs periodically (every 15--60 minutes) when the plant has settled:

- Advantages: Simpler models, faster computation, well-understood theory
- Limitations: Cannot handle transient conditions, must wait for steady state

#strong[Dynamic RTO] uses dynamic models that capture transient behavior:

- Advantages: Can optimize during transients, faster response
- Limitations: More complex models, higher computational cost, harder to validate

=== Steady-State Detection
<steady-state-detection>
Before running steady-state RTO, the system must verify that the plant is at steady state. A common test is the #strong[R-statistic] applied to key process variables:

$ R = 1 / N sum_(i = 1)^N (frac(y_i - macron(y), sigma_y))^2 $

If $R$ is below a threshold (typically 1.0--2.0), the process is considered at steady state.

=== Data Reconciliation
<data-reconciliation>
Measurement errors are inevitable. Data reconciliation adjusts measured values to satisfy material and energy balances while minimizing the total adjustment:

$ min_x quad sum_i (frac(x_i - y_i, sigma_i))^2 $

subject to:

$ A dot.op x = 0 quad upright("(material balance)") $

where $y_i$ is the measured value, $x_i$ is the reconciled value, and $sigma_i$ is the measurement uncertainty.

=== Model Update (Parameter Estimation)
<model-update-parameter-estimation>
The process model parameters (e.g., well productivity indices, heat transfer coefficients, compressor efficiencies) are adjusted to minimize the discrepancy between model predictions and reconciled measurements:

$ min_theta quad sum_i (frac(x_i^(upright("model")) \( theta \) - x_i^(upright("plant")), sigma_i))^2 $

where $theta$ is the vector of model parameters.

This step is critical: an optimization based on an inaccurate model will produce poor set points, potentially worse than the current operation.

=== Implementation Challenges
<implementation-challenges>
Real-time optimization faces several practical challenges that must be addressed for successful deployment:

#strong[Model fidelity]: The process model must be accurate enough to predict the effect of set point changes. This requires regular validation against plant data and parameter re-tuning. A common metric is the #strong[model prediction error] for key variables:

$ upright("MPE")_i = frac(\| y_i^(upright("model")) - y_i^(upright("plant")) \|, y_i^(upright("plant"))) times 100 % $

Acceptable MPE is typically \< 5% for flow rates and \< 2% for temperatures and pressures.

#strong[Steady-state assumption]: Standard RTO requires steady-state conditions, but real plants are rarely truly at steady state. Frequent disturbances (slug flow, well cycling, compressor surging) can prevent the RTO from running. In practice, the steady-state detection logic must be tuned to balance responsiveness with robustness.

#strong[Move suppression]: The optimizer may suggest large set point changes that are impractical or destabilizing. Move suppression limits the maximum change per RTO cycle:

$ \| x_(k + 1) - x_k \| lt.eq Delta x_(upright("max")) $

This prevents oscillation and ensures the plant transitions smoothly to the new optimum.

#strong[Operator acceptance]: RTO recommendations must be understandable and trustworthy. Operators need to see #emph[why] a change is recommended and #emph[what will happen] if they implement it. This requires clear visualization of the current vs.~optimized state and the expected benefits.

=== RTO Performance Metrics
<rto-performance-metrics>
The value of RTO is measured by comparing actual production with the pre-RTO baseline:

$ upright("RTO Benefit") = sum_(d = 1)^(N_(upright("days"))) [f \( x_(upright("RTO") \, d) \) - f \( x_(upright("baseline") \, d) \)] $

Typical RTO benefits in offshore production are 2--5% increase in oil production or 3--8% reduction in energy consumption. For a platform producing 50,000 bbl/day, a 3% improvement at \$70/bbl is approximately \$1.1 million per day --- easily justifying the investment.

