This chapter focuses primarily on the daily-to-monthly operational optimization timescale, where process simulation is most directly applicable.

=== Production Optimization as a Life-of-Field Problem
<production-optimization-as-a-life-of-field-problem>
The production optimization problem changes continuously over the life of a field:

#strong[Early life (plateau production):] Reservoir pressure is high, and the wells can deliver more fluid than the facilities can process. The bottleneck is typically topside equipment --- separator capacity, compressor power, or pipeline pressure drop. Optimization focuses on maximizing throughput up to equipment limits.

#strong[Mid-life (declining reservoir pressure):] As reservoir pressure declines, the wellhead pressure decreases and the gas-to-oil ratio (GOR) changes. The compression ratio increases, requiring more compressor power per unit of export gas. The bottleneck may shift from separator capacity to compressor power.

#strong[Late life (high water cut / low pressure):] Water production increases, consuming separator and pump capacity. Reservoir pressure is low, requiring maximum compression and possibly gas lift. Multiple equipment items may be simultaneously near their limits. Optimization becomes a complex multi-constraint problem.

This life-cycle evolution means that the #strong[bottleneck identity shifts over time], and the optimal operating strategy must evolve accordingly. A production optimization system that identifies the current bottleneck and quantifies the spare capacity of other equipment enables proactive planning for future constraints.

=== Economic Value of Production Optimization
<economic-value-of-production-optimization>
The economic impact of production optimization is substantial. Even small improvements in production efficiency translate to large revenue gains:

#strong[Example]: A platform producing 100,000 bbl/day of oil at \$70/bbl generates \$7M/day. A 2% production increase through optimization yields an additional \$51M/year --- far exceeding the cost of implementing an optimization system.

Industry studies report typical optimization gains of: - 1--3% throughput increase through separator pressure optimization - 2--5% through gas lift allocation optimization - 3--8% through debottlenecking guided by constraint analysis - 5--15% through comprehensive facility-wide optimization

The value compounds when optimization prevents costly equipment trips, reduces flaring, and extends the economic life of the field by maintaining production during the decline phase.

#horizontalrule

== Equipment Capacity Constraints: Theory
<equipment-capacity-constraints-theory>
Every piece of process equipment has physical limits that cannot be exceeded without risking damage, safety hazards, or loss of function. Understanding these limits mathematically is the foundation of production optimization.

=== The Utilization Factor
<the-utilization-factor>
The #strong[utilization factor] provides a unified metric for comparing how close any equipment item is to its capacity limit:

$ U_i = Q_(i \, upright("actual")) / Q_(i \, upright("max")) $

where $U_i$ is the utilization factor for equipment item $i$, $Q_(i \, upright("actual"))$ is the actual operating duty, and $Q_(i \, upright("max"))$ is the maximum allowable duty. The equipment with the highest utilization factor is the #strong[bottleneck] --- it limits the overall system throughput:

$ Q_(upright("system,max")) = frac(Q_(upright("current")), max_i \( U_i \)) $

=== Constraint Classification
<constraint-classification>
Not all constraints are equal. NeqSim classifies constraints into three severity levels:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 4,
    align: (auto,auto,auto,auto,),
    table.header([Type], [Description], [Consequence of Violation], [Example],),
    table.hline(),
    [#strong[HARD]], [Absolute equipment limits], [Trip, mechanical failure, safety hazard], [Compressor overspeed, PSV capacity],
    [#strong[SOFT]], [Efficiency or operational limits], [Reduced efficiency, accelerated wear], [Design flow rate, temperature approach],
    [#strong[DESIGN]], [Design basis values], [Information only --- no operational impact], [Nameplate capacity, design point],
  )]
  , kind: table
  )

This classification enables the optimizer to distinguish between constraints that make a solution physically impossible (HARD) and those that merely make it suboptimal (SOFT).

=== Separator Capacity Constraints
<separator-capacity-constraints>
Separator capacity is governed by three independent criteria --- the minimum of the three determines the overall separator capacity.

#strong[Gas handling capacity] is limited by the Souders-Brown equation (Souders and Brown, 1934):

$ v_(upright("gas,max")) = K_(upright("SB")) dot.op sqrt(frac(rho_L - rho_G, rho_G)) $

where $K_(upright("SB"))$ is the Souders-Brown coefficient (m/s), $rho_L$ is the liquid density (kg/m³), and $rho_G$ is the gas density (kg/m³). The coefficient depends on separator type and internal devices:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 3,
    align: (auto,auto,auto,),
    table.header([Separator Configuration], [$K_(upright("SB"))$ (m/s)], [Typical Application],),
    table.hline(),
    [Vertical, no internals], [0.04--0.06], [Scrubbers, test separators],
    [Vertical, wire mesh demister], [0.07--0.11], [Inlet separators],
    [Horizontal, half-full], [0.12--0.17], [Production separators],
    [Horizontal, wire mesh demister], [0.15--0.21], [Two-phase separators],
    [Horizontal, vane pack], [0.18--0.25], [High-capacity separators],
  )]
  , kind: table
  )

The maximum gas flow rate through the separator is:

$ Q_(upright("gas,max")) = v_(upright("gas,max")) dot.op A_(upright("gas")) $

where $A_(upright("gas"))$ is the cross-sectional area available for gas flow. For a horizontal separator with liquid occupying fraction $f = h \/ D$ of the diameter, the gas area is:

$ A_(upright("gas")) = frac(pi D^2, 4) dot.op \( 1 - f \) $

The gas load factor utilization is:

$ U_(upright("gas")) = v_(upright("gas,actual")) / v_(upright("gas,max")) = Q_(upright("gas,actual")) / Q_(upright("gas,max")) $

When $U_(upright("gas")) > 1.0$, liquid droplet carry-over increases significantly, leading to poor separation performance and downstream contamination.

#strong[Liquid handling capacity] is determined by the minimum retention time required for gas bubbles to rise out of the liquid phase and for water droplets to settle:

$ t_(upright("ret")) = V_(upright("liq")) / Q_(upright("liq")) $

where $V_(upright("liq"))$ is the liquid volume in the separator (m³) and $Q_(upright("liq"))$ is the total liquid volumetric flow rate (m³/s). Typical minimum retention times:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 3,
    align: (auto,auto,auto,),
    table.header([Service], [Oil Retention Time (min)], [Water Retention Time (min)],),
    table.hline(),
    [HP separator, light oil (API \> 30)], [1--3], [1--2],
    [HP separator, medium oil], [3--5], [2--3],
    [LP separator, light oil], [2--4], [2--3],
    [Three-phase separator], [5--10], [5--15],
  )]
  , kind: table
  )

The liquid capacity utilization is:

$ U_(upright("liq")) = t_(upright("ret,min")) / t_(upright("ret,actual")) = frac(Q_(upright("liq,actual")) dot.op t_(upright("ret,min")), V_(upright("liq"))) $

#strong[Gas-liquid interface area] provides a third constraint for horizontal separators, limiting the rate at which gas can disengage from the liquid:

$ sigma_(upright("GL")) = Q_(upright("liq")) / A_(upright("GL")) \, #h(2em) U_(upright("GL")) = sigma_(upright("GL")) / sigma_(upright("GL,max")) $

where $sigma_(upright("GL,max")) approx 0.005$--$0.015$ m³/m²·s depending on oil API gravity and GOR.

The overall separator utilization is the maximum of all active criteria:

$ U_(upright("sep")) = max \( U_(upright("gas")) \, U_(upright("liq")) \, U_(upright("GL")) \) $

The limiting criterion depends on operating conditions. For a gas-dominated field, $U_(upright("gas"))$ typically governs. For a mature field with high water cut, $U_(upright("liq"))$ often becomes the bottleneck. This shifting behavior is precisely what makes automated bottleneck detection valuable --- it identifies the active constraint without manual calculation.

=== Compressor Capacity Constraints
<compressor-capacity-constraints>
Compressors have multiple simultaneous constraints forming an operating envelope. The compressor operating point must lie within the region bounded by the surge line, stonewall (choke) line, maximum speed, minimum speed, and power limit curves.

- #strong[Surge limit] (HARD): Minimum flow for aerodynamic stability. Below surge, flow reversal causes severe mechanical damage at 1--10 Hz cycles. The surge margin is defined as:

$ S M = frac(Q_(upright("actual")) - Q_(upright("surge")), Q_(upright("actual"))) times 100 % $

A typical minimum surge margin is 10%. Operating below this margin requires anti-surge recycle, which wastes energy but protects the compressor.

- #strong[Power limit] (HARD): Shaft power must not exceed driver capacity. For gas turbine drivers, the available power decreases with ambient temperature (derating):

$ W_(upright("shaft")) = frac(dot(m) dot.op Delta h_(upright("isen")), eta_(upright("isen"))) + W_(upright("mech losses")) $

$ W_(upright("GT,derated")) = W_(upright("GT,ISO")) dot.op (1 - alpha dot.op \( T_(upright("amb")) - T_(upright("ISO")) \)) $

where $alpha$ is the derating coefficient, typically 0.5--0.8% per °C for aeroderivative gas turbines. The power utilization is:

$ U_(upright("power")) = W_(upright("shaft")) / W_(upright("driver,derated")) $

- #strong[Speed limit] (HARD): Maximum impeller rotational speed is set by mechanical stress limits. Centrifugal compressor tip speeds above \~350 m/s risk mechanical failure.

- #strong[Stonewall (choke) limit]: Maximum volumetric throughput when the gas velocity at the impeller throat approaches sonic velocity. Beyond this point, no further increase in flow is possible regardless of downstream pressure reduction.

- #strong[Discharge temperature limit] (SOFT): Excessive discharge temperature accelerates seal and lubricant degradation. Typical limit: 150--180°C for dry gas seals.

The polytropic head relates compression ratio to gas properties:

$ H_p = Z_(upright("avg")) dot.op R / M dot.op T_1 dot.op frac(n, n - 1) dot.op [(P_2 / P_1)^(\( n - 1 \) \/ n) - 1] $

where $n$ is the polytropic exponent, $R$ is the universal gas constant, $T_1$ is suction temperature, $M$ is molecular weight, and $Z_(upright("avg"))$ is the average compressibility factor.

The combined compressor utilization considers all constraints:

$ U_(upright("comp")) = max \( U_(upright("surge")) \, U_(upright("power")) \, U_(upright("speed")) \, U_(upright("stonewall")) \, U_(upright("T,discharge")) \) $

In practice, the power limit is often the binding constraint for export compressors (especially in hot climates where gas turbine derating is significant), while the surge limit governs during turndown operations.

=== Valve Capacity Constraints
<valve-capacity-constraints>
Control valves are characterized by their flow coefficient $C_v$, which relates flow rate to pressure drop across the valve. For liquid flow (ISA/IEC 60534):

$ Q = N_1 dot.op F_L dot.op C_v dot.op sqrt(frac(Delta P, rho \/ rho_0)) $

For gas flow under subcritical conditions:

$ W = N_6 dot.op F_gamma dot.op C_v dot.op Y dot.op sqrt(x dot.op P_1 dot.op rho_1) $

where $Y = 1 - x \/ \( 3 x_T \)$ is the expansion factor, $x = Delta P \/ P_1$ is the pressure drop ratio, and $x_T$ is the critical pressure drop ratio for the valve.

The valve opening utilization compares required $C_v$ to installed $C_v$:

$ U_(upright("valve")) = C_(v \, upright("required")) / C_(v \, upright("max")) $

Good control practice requires operation between 20% and 80% valve opening. Below 20%, the valve is nearly closed and may exhibit instability. Above 80%, there is insufficient control authority to handle disturbances. A fully open valve (100%) provides no control margin and limits system throughput --- any increase in flow would require a larger valve.

For choke valves in well service, the flow equation includes critical flow effects and multiphase corrections:

$ C_(v \, upright("required")) = Q_(upright("total")) / sqrt(Delta P \/ rho_m) dot.op F_(upright("multiphase")) $

The $F_(upright("multiphase"))$ correction accounts for flashing, two-phase flow, and gas release, and can be 1.2--2.5 times larger than the single-phase $C_v$ requirement.

=== Pipeline Capacity Constraints
<pipeline-capacity-constraints>
Pipelines are constrained by multiple criteria, any of which can limit throughput.

#strong[Erosional velocity] (API RP 14E): The mixture velocity must not exceed the erosional velocity limit to prevent pipe wall erosion:

$ v_(upright("eros")) = C / sqrt(rho_m) $

where $C$ is the empirical constant (100--300 in field units, with C = 100 being the most conservative) and $rho_m$ is the mixture density (lb/ft³ in US customary or kg/m³ with adjusted $C$). The velocity utilization is:

$ U_(upright("vel")) = v_(upright("actual")) / v_(upright("eros")) $

#strong[Flow-Induced Vibration (FIV)]: For multiphase flow, flow-induced vibration is assessed using the DNVGL RP-F101 criteria:

- #strong[Likelihood of Failure (LOF)]: $rho_m v_m^2 \/ upright("LOF")_(upright("limit"))$
- #strong[Force RMS]: $F_(upright("RMS")) \/ F_(upright("RMS,limit"))$, where $F_(upright("RMS"))$ is the root-mean-square force from slug impact

$ U_(upright("FIV")) = max (frac(rho_m v_m^2, upright("LOF")_(upright("limit"))) \, F_(upright("RMS")) / F_(upright("RMS,limit"))) $

#strong[Pressure drop]: The available pressure drop between the upstream vessel and the receiving facility limits the flow:

$ U_(Delta P) = frac(Delta P_(upright("actual")), Delta P_(upright("available"))) $

For long subsea pipelines, the available pressure drop may be the primary constraint. The Beggs-and-Brill correlation (or equivalent) computes the frictional and gravitational pressure drop:

$ frac(d P, d L) = frac(f rho_m v_m^2, 2 D) + rho_m g sin theta + rho_m v_m frac(d v_m, d L) $

#strong[MAOP]: The Maximum Allowable Operating Pressure is a regulatory/design limit that cannot be exceeded under any conditions.

The overall pipeline utilization is:

$ U_(upright("pipe")) = max \( U_(upright("vel")) \, U_(upright("FIV")) \, U_(Delta P) \, U_(upright("MAOP")) \) $

=== Pump Capacity Constraints
<pump-capacity-constraints>
Pumps are limited by three primary constraints:

#strong[Net Positive Suction Head (NPSH)]: The available NPSH must exceed the required NPSH to avoid cavitation:

$ upright("NPSH")_A = frac(P_(upright("suction")) - P_(upright("vapor")), rho g) + frac(v^2, 2 g) + z_(upright("suction")) $

$ U_(upright("NPSH")) = upright("NPSH")_R / upright("NPSH")_A $

The NPSH margin should be at least 10--20% ($U_(upright("NPSH")) < 0.83$--$0.90$) to account for transients and instrument uncertainty. Cavitation causes rapid impeller erosion, loss of head, and increased vibration.

#strong[Power]: Pump power consumption is:

$ W_(upright("pump")) = frac(Q dot.op Delta P, eta_(upright("pump")) dot.op eta_(upright("motor"))) \, #h(2em) U_(upright("power")) = W_(upright("pump")) / W_(upright("driver,max")) $

#strong[Pump curve operating range]: The pump must operate within the stable region of its head-flow curve. At very low flow ("minimum continuous flow"), internal recirculation causes vibration and heating. At very high flow, NPSH requirements increase rapidly.

=== Heat Exchanger Capacity Constraints
<heat-exchanger-capacity-constraints>
Heat exchangers are constrained by thermal duty and pressure drop:

$ Q = U dot.op A dot.op Delta T_(upright("LMTD")) dot.op F_t $

where $U$ is the overall heat transfer coefficient, $A$ is the heat transfer area, $Delta T_(upright("LMTD"))$ is the log-mean temperature difference, and $F_t$ is the LMTD correction factor for multi-pass configurations.

Fouling reduces the effective $U$ value over time, reducing the available duty. The fouling utilization is:

$ U_(upright("foul")) = frac(U_(upright("clean")), U_(upright("clean")) - R_f dot.op U_(upright("clean"))^2) dot.op frac(1, A dot.op Delta T_(upright("LMTD"))) dot.op Q_(upright("required")) $

The approach temperature ($T_(upright("hot,out")) - T_(upright("cold,in"))$ or $T_(upright("hot,in")) - T_(upright("cold,out"))$) is a practical constraint --- if the approach temperature is too small, the exchanger is oversized relative to the need; if too large, it may be undersized.

