== Depressurization and Blowdown
<depressurization-and-blowdown>
=== Why Depressurization Matters
<why-depressurization-matters>
Emergency depressurization (EDP) is the controlled venting of pressurized equipment to a flare or vent system in response to a fire or gas release. The objectives are:

+ #strong[Reduce the stress]: Lower the vessel pressure (and hence wall stress) before the metal temperature rises to the point of rupture
+ #strong[Minimize hydrocarbon inventory]: Reduce the amount of flammable material available to feed a fire
+ #strong[Achieve target pressure within the required time]: API 521 and NORSOK S-001 require depressurization to 50% of design pressure or 6.9 barg (whichever is lower) within 15 minutes

=== Physics of Blowdown
<physics-of-blowdown>
During blowdown, the pressure drops rapidly and the gas expands. This expansion causes cooling through the Joule--Thomson effect. The minimum temperature during blowdown determines whether the vessel material can withstand the conditions without brittle fracture.

The governing equations for a vessel blowdown (assuming ideal gas expansion as a first approximation) are:

#strong[Pressure decay]:

$ frac(d P, d t) = - dot(m)_(upright("out")) / V frac(Z R T, M_w) $

#strong[Temperature change] (isentropic expansion with heat transfer from walls):

$ frac(d T, d t) = T / P frac(d P, d t) (frac(gamma - 1, gamma)) + frac(h_(upright("wall")) A_(upright("wall")), M C_v) \( T_(upright("wall")) - T \) $

where $gamma$ is the heat capacity ratio $C_p \/ C_v$, $h_(upright("wall"))$ is the wall-to-fluid heat transfer coefficient, and $A_(upright("wall"))$ is the internal surface area.

The blowdown flow rate through the orifice depends on whether the flow is critical (choked) or subcritical:

$ dot(m)_(upright("out")) = C_d A_(upright("orifice")) P sqrt(frac(M_w, Z R T)) dot.op phi.alt \( gamma \, P_(upright("back")) \/ P \) $

where $phi.alt$ is the flow function that accounts for choked vs subcritical flow.

