== Model Calibration and Data Reconciliation
<model-calibration-and-data-reconciliation>
=== Why Calibration Is Needed
<why-calibration-is-needed>
Even the best process model will not exactly match plant measurements because:

- #strong[Model simplifications]: The model may not capture every detail (heat losses, minor leaks, recycle effects)
- #strong[Parameter uncertainty]: Equipment parameters degrade over time (fouling, wear, catalyst deactivation)
- #strong[Measurement uncertainty]: Instruments have finite accuracy and drift between calibrations
- #strong[Composition changes]: Feed composition varies continuously, but is measured infrequently (lab samples)

Calibration adjusts model parameters to minimize the discrepancy between simulated and measured values, subject to measurement uncertainty bounds.

=== Data Reconciliation
<data-reconciliation>
Data reconciliation exploits the fact that process measurements must satisfy conservation laws (mass, energy). The reconciled measurements are the "most likely true values" given the measurements and their uncertainties:

$ min_x quad \( x - x_m \)^T V^(- 1) \( x - x_m \) $

$ upright("subject to:") quad A x = 0 $

where $x$ is the vector of reconciled values, $x_m$ is the vector of measured values, $V$ is the measurement error covariance matrix, and $A x = 0$ represents the conservation constraints.

The solution is:

$ x^(*) = x_m - V A^T \( A V A^T \)^(- 1) A x_m $

Data reconciliation improves measurement quality and detects #strong[gross errors] (instrument failures) by examining the reconciliation residuals.

=== Parameter Estimation
<parameter-estimation>
Given reconciled data, parameter estimation determines the model parameters that best reproduce the observed behavior:

$ min_theta quad sum_(k = 1)^N (frac(y_k^(upright("model")) \( theta \) - y_k^(upright("measured")), sigma_k))^2 $

where $theta$ is the vector of adjustable parameters (e.g., heat transfer coefficients, compressor efficiency, separator internals efficiency), $y_k^(upright("model"))$ is the model prediction, $y_k^(upright("measured"))$ is the measured value, and $sigma_k$ is the measurement standard deviation.

Common parameters adjusted during calibration:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 3,
    align: (auto,auto,auto,),
    table.header([Parameter], [Equipment], [Adjustment Range],),
    table.hline(),
    [Overall heat transfer coefficient $U A$], [Heat exchangers], [±50% (fouling)],
    [Polytropic efficiency], [Compressors], [±10% (degradation)],
    [Valve $C_v$], [Control valves], [±20% (erosion, deposits)],
    [Separator efficiency], [Separators], [±15% (internals damage)],
    [Pipe roughness], [Pipelines], [±30% (corrosion, deposits)],
    [Feed composition], [Inlet streams], [Per lab analysis uncertainty],
  )]
