== Model Predictive Control (MPC)
<model-predictive-control-mpc>
=== MPC Fundamentals
<mpc-fundamentals>
Model Predictive Control extends RTO to a dynamic setting. Instead of optimizing steady-state set points, MPC optimizes a sequence of future control moves over a #strong[prediction horizon]:

$ min_(u_0 \, u_1 \, dots.h \, u_(N - 1)) quad sum_(k = 0)^N [\( y_k - y_k^(upright("ref")) \)^T Q \( y_k - y_k^(upright("ref")) \) + Delta u_k^T R thin Delta u_k] $

$ upright("subject to:") quad x_(k + 1) = f \( x_k \, u_k \) $

$ y_k = g \( x_k \) $

$ u_min lt.eq u_k lt.eq u_max $

$ y_min lt.eq y_k lt.eq y_max $

where $y_k$ are the controlled variables, $u_k$ are the manipulated variables, $Delta u_k = u_k - u_(k - 1)$ are the control moves, $Q$ and $R$ are weighting matrices, and $N$ is the prediction horizon.

MPC offers several advantages over PID-based control:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 3,
    align: (auto,auto,auto,),
    table.header([Feature], [PID], [MPC],),
    table.hline(),
    [Number of loops], [Single variable], [Multi-variable],
    [Constraint handling], [Limited (output clamping)], [Explicit constraints],
    [Anticipation], [None (reactive only)], [Predicts future behavior],
    [Interaction], [Tuned independently], [Coordinated],
    [Model requirements], [First-order + dead time], [Full dynamic model],
  )]
  , kind: table
  )

=== MPC in Oil and Gas Production
<mpc-in-oil-and-gas-production>
Common MPC applications in production facilities:

- #strong[Compressor optimization]: Coordinate speed, suction valve, and recycle valve to minimize power while maintaining throughput and surge margin
- #strong[Separator train optimization]: Coordinate pressures across HP/MP/LP separators to maximize liquid recovery
- #strong[Gas processing]: Control temperature, pressure, and TEG circulation in the dehydration unit
- #strong[Export quality management]: Maintain gas dew point and H₂S specifications while maximizing throughput

=== Integration of MPC with NeqSim
<integration-of-mpc-with-neqsim>
While NeqSim does not include a built-in MPC solver, its dynamic simulation capability provides the process model that MPC requires. The integration pattern is:

+ Build the NeqSim process model (Chapter 20)
+ Identify the MPC variables (CVs, MVs, DVs)
+ Generate step response data by perturbing each MV and recording the CV responses
+ Build the MPC model (typically in a dedicated MPC package)
+ At each control interval, update the NeqSim model with plant data and provide it to the MPC as the current state

