== Edge Computing and Deployment
<edge-computing-and-deployment>
=== Edge vs Cloud Architecture
<edge-vs-cloud-architecture>
Digital twins can be deployed at three architectural levels:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 4,
    align: (auto,auto,auto,auto,),
    table.header([Level], [Location], [Latency], [Use Case],),
    table.hline(),
    [#strong[Edge]], [On-site server or gateway], [\< 1 s], [Real-time control, safety],
    [#strong[Fog]], [Regional data center], [1--10 s], [Production optimization],
    [#strong[Cloud]], [Cloud platform (Azure, AWS)], [10--100 s], [Analytics, reporting, ML training],
  )]
  , kind: table
  )

For Level 3 and 4 digital twins, edge deployment is essential because:

- Low latency for closed-loop control
- Continued operation during network outages
- Reduced bandwidth (only aggregated results sent to cloud)
- Data sovereignty (sensitive process data stays on-site)

=== NeqSim in Edge/Cloud Architecture
<neqsim-in-edgecloud-architecture>
NeqSim's Java-based architecture is well-suited for edge deployment:

- #strong[JVM availability]: Java runs on virtually all edge computing platforms
- #strong[Compact footprint]: The NeqSim JAR is \< 50 MB including all dependencies
- #strong[No GPU required]: Thermodynamic calculations use CPU only
- #strong[JSON API]: The automation API communicates via JSON, compatible with REST/MQTT/OPC UA
- #strong[Compressed state transfer]: Model states can be serialized to compressed bytes for efficient network transfer

A typical edge deployment pattern:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────┐     ┌──────────────────┐
│         Edge Server             │     │      Cloud        │
│                                 │     │                   │
│  ┌──────────┐  ┌────────────┐  │     │  ┌────────────┐  │
│  │ OPC UA    │→ │  NeqSim    │  │───→ │  │ Analytics  │  │
