The practical consequence is that onshore plants are designed to extract maximum value from the gas stream, while offshore platforms are designed to achieve basic separation with minimum equipment.

=== Typical Onshore Gas Plant Block Diagram
<typical-onshore-gas-plant-block-diagram>
A complete onshore gas plant processes raw gas through the following sequence of operations:

+ #strong[Inlet receiving] --- Slug catcher, inlet separator, free water knockout
+ #strong[Gas sweetening] --- Amine absorption for CO$""_2$ and H$""_2$S removal
+ #strong[Dehydration] --- TEG absorption with regeneration
+ #strong[NGL recovery] --- Turboexpander, JT valve, or mechanical refrigeration
+ #strong[Fractionation] --- Demethanizer, deethanizer, depropanizer, debutanizer
+ #strong[Sulfur recovery] --- Claus process (if sour gas)
+ #strong[Tail gas treatment] --- SCOT or similar process
+ #strong[Product storage and loading] --- Refrigerated/pressurized storage, truck/rail/pipeline
+ #strong[Utilities] --- Power generation, steam, cooling water, instrument air, flare

#figure(image("figures_ch33/ch22_onshore_plant_block_diagram.png"),
  caption: [
    Block diagram of a complete onshore gas processing plant
  ]
)

#emph[Figure 22.1: Block flow diagram showing the major processing sections of an onshore gas plant. Streams shown are gas (blue), liquid hydrocarbon (green), water (gray), and acid gas (red).]

Not every plant has all of these sections. A "lean gas" plant processing dry pipeline gas may only need dehydration and hydrocarbon dew point control. A "rich gas" plant with high C$""_3$+ content and sour gas needs the full processing chain. The plant configuration is driven by feed gas composition, product specifications, and economics.

