== Fractionation Train
<fractionation-train>
=== Overview of NGL Fractionation
<overview-of-ngl-fractionation>
The NGL stream from the recovery section is a mixture of C$""_2$--C$""_7$+ hydrocarbons. To produce individual products (ethane, propane, butane, natural gasoline), this mixture must be separated in a series of distillation columns called the #strong[fractionation train].

The standard fractionation sequence separates the lightest component overhead first:

+ #strong[Demethanizer] --- Removes methane (and nitrogen) from the NGL stream. The overhead (residue gas) joins the sales gas. The bottom product is the C$""_2$+ NGL.
+ #strong[Deethanizer] --- Separates ethane (overhead) from C$""_3$+ (bottoms). Ethane is sold as petrochemical feedstock or reinjected into the gas stream. Operates at 20--30 bara, with overhead temperature of −10 to +5°C.
+ #strong[Depropanizer] --- Separates propane (overhead) from C$""_4$+ (bottoms). Propane is sold as LPG or petrochemical feedstock. Operates at 15--20 bara, with overhead temperature of 40--55°C.
+ #strong[Debutanizer] --- Separates butanes (overhead, mixed i-C$""_4$ and n-C$""_4$) from C$""_5$+ natural gasoline (bottoms). Operates at 5--8 bara.

Some plants include an additional #strong[butane splitter] to separate isobutane (for alkylation feedstock) from normal butane.

=== Key Design Variables
<key-design-variables>
Each fractionation column is designed to achieve a specified #strong[product purity] and #strong[product recovery]:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 5,
    align: (auto,auto,auto,auto,auto,),
    table.header([Column], [Key Spec], [Overhead Purity], [Bottoms Purity], [Typical Stages],),
    table.hline(),
    [Demethanizer], [C$""_1$ in overhead], [\>98% methane], [\<1% methane in NGL], [15--30],
    [Deethanizer], [C$""_2$ recovery], [\>95% ethane], [\<2% ethane in C$""_3$+], [25--35],
    [Depropanizer], [C$""_3$ purity], [\>95% propane (HD-5)], [\<2% propane in C$""_4$+], [30--40],
    [Debutanizer], [C$""_4$ recovery], [\>95% butanes], [\<2% butane in gasoline], [25--35],
  )]
  , kind: table
  )

#emph[Table 22.6: Typical fractionation column specifications.]

The reflux ratio determines the trade-off between column size (capital cost) and energy consumption (operating cost). The minimum reflux ratio is calculated from the Underwood equations:

$ R_min = frac(1, alpha_(L K) - 1) [frac(alpha_(L K) dot.op x_(L K \, D), 1 - q) - frac(x_(H K \, D), 1 - q)] $

where $alpha_(L K)$ is the relative volatility of the light key, $x_(L K \, D)$ and $x_(H K \, D)$ are the light and heavy key mole fractions in the distillate, and $q$ is the feed quality.

The actual reflux ratio is typically 1.1--1.3 times the minimum:

$ R = \( 1.1 upright(" to ") 1.3 \) dot.op R_min $

