== Sulfur Recovery
<sulfur-recovery>
=== The Claus Process
<the-claus-process>
When sour gas contains significant quantities of H$""_2$S (typically \>10 tpd sulfur production), the acid gas from the amine regenerator is processed in a #strong[Claus sulfur recovery unit (SRU)] to convert H$""_2$S to elemental sulfur.

The Claus process is a two-stage chemical reaction:

#strong[Stage 1 --- Thermal stage (Reaction furnace, 1000--1400°C):]

$ 2 upright("H")_2 upright("S") + 3 upright("O")_2 arrow.r 2 upright("SO")_2 + 2 upright("H")_2 upright("O") quad Delta H = - 518 upright(" kJ/mol") $

One-third of the H$""_2$S is burned with controlled air to produce SO$""_2$. The hot gases are cooled in a waste heat boiler, producing high-pressure steam.

#strong[Stage 2 --- Catalytic stages (Alumina catalyst, 200--350°C):]

$ 2 upright("H")_2 upright("S") + upright("SO")_2 harpoons.rtlb 3 upright("S") + 2 upright("H")_2 upright("O") quad Delta H = - 108 upright(" kJ/mol") $

The remaining H$""_2$S reacts with the SO$""_2$ over an alumina (Al$""_2$O$""_3$) catalyst to produce elemental sulfur. Two or three catalytic stages are used in series, each followed by a sulfur condenser.

The overall Claus reaction is:

$ 3 upright("H")_2 upright("S") + 1.5 upright("O")_2 arrow.r 3 upright("S") + 3 upright("H")_2 upright("O") $

The sulfur recovery efficiency of a well-designed Claus unit is:

#figure(
  align(center)[#table(
    columns: 2,
    align: (auto,auto,),
    table.header([Number of Catalytic Stages], [Recovery Efficiency],),
    table.hline(),
    [2 stages], [94--96%],
    [3 stages], [97--98%],
  )]
  , kind: table
  )

#emph[Table 22.7: Claus process sulfur recovery efficiency.]

=== Tail Gas Treatment
<tail-gas-treatment>
Environmental regulations require overall sulfur recovery of 99.5--99.9%, which exceeds the capability of the Claus process alone. #strong[Tail gas treatment units (TGTU)] process the Claus tail gas to recover the remaining sulfur compounds.

The most common TGTU technologies are:

- #strong[SCOT process] (Shell Claus Off-gas Treatment): Reduces all sulfur species to H$""_2$S, then absorbs the H$""_2$S in an amine unit and recycles it to the Claus feed.
- #strong[Cansolv process]: Direct SO$""_2$ capture from the incinerated tail gas using a regenerable amine solvent.
- #strong[BSR/MDEA]: Similar to SCOT but uses MDEA for selective H$""_2$S absorption.

The SCOT process first reduces all sulfur species to H$""_2$S over a cobalt-molybdenum catalyst:

$ upright("SO")_2 + 3 upright("H")_2 arrow.r upright("H")_2 upright("S") + 2 upright("H")_2 upright("O") $

$ upright("S") + upright("H")_2 arrow.r upright("H")_2 upright("S") $

$ upright("COS") + upright("H")_2 upright("O") arrow.r upright("H")_2 upright("S") + upright("CO")_2 $

The resulting gas, containing 1--3% H$""_2$S, is cooled and fed to a small amine absorber. The rich amine is regenerated and the acid gas recycled to the Claus SRU.

