=== Loading Systems
<loading-systems>
Products are shipped by pipeline, truck, rail car, or ship:

- #strong[Sales gas]: Pipeline to market (continuous)
- #strong[Ethane]: Pipeline to petrochemical complex (continuous)
- #strong[Propane/LPG]: Pipeline, truck, rail, or ship (batch)
- #strong[Butane]: Pipeline, truck, or ship (batch)
- #strong[Natural gasoline]: Pipeline, truck, or ship (batch)
- #strong[Sulfur]: Truck, rail, or ship as molten liquid or formed solid blocks

Loading systems include vapor recovery units to capture displaced vapors during liquid loading and return them to the plant for reprocessing.

#horizontalrule

== Plant Utility Systems
<plant-utility-systems>
=== Power Generation
<power-generation>
Onshore gas plants require large amounts of electrical power for compressor drives, pumps, cooling fans, lighting, and instrumentation. Power is typically supplied by:

- #strong[Grid electricity]: The most cost-effective option where available
- #strong[Gas turbine generators]: Using fuel gas from the plant, providing both power and waste heat
- #strong[Steam turbine generators]: Using steam from Claus waste heat boilers or dedicated boilers

Typical power consumption for a 500 MMscfd gas plant is 50--100 MW, dominated by compression.

=== Steam System
<steam-system>
Steam is required for: - Amine regenerator reboiler - TEG regenerator reboiler - Fractionation column reboilers - Steam turbine drives - Building heating, tank heating

Steam is generated in package boilers, waste heat recovery units (from gas turbine exhaust or Claus furnace), and process heat recovery.

=== Cooling System
<cooling-system>
Onshore plants use #strong[cooling towers] (evaporative cooling) or #strong[air-cooled exchangers] (fin-fan) for heat rejection, depending on water availability and ambient conditions. Cooling water systems typically provide water at 25--30°C (tropical) or 15--20°C (temperate).

